AUTHORITIES arrested a senior police officer yesterday, as they continue to crack down on alleged cases of corruption involving government workers.
The spokesperson of the Zimbabwe AntiCorruption Commission (Zacc), John Makamure, confirmed to the Daily News that they had nabbed the officer commanding Matabeleland North, Erasmus Makodza, over alleged abuse of
office. Makamure said Makodza would appear in court today. “He is being charged with criminal abuse of duty, alternatively concealing from a principal a personal interest in a transaction. “He allegedly influenced ZRP (Zimbabwe Republic Police) to enter into an agreement with a lady that he has a child with … to lease a ZRP farm in Mashonaland East. “It happened when he was an officer commanding Mashonaland East,” Makamure told the Daily News. It is being alleged that the lease of the ZRP farm was for Makodza’s personal benefit. Makodza has held several senior positions in the police force, including being the officer commanding Criminal Investigation Department (CID) in Bulawayo, officer commanding Mashonaland East and Harare provinces, as well as the commander for the historic 2018 elections, amongst other deployments. His arrest comes as authorities have in recent months descended on high-ranking police officers for alleged cases of graft, criminal abuse of office and obstruction of justice. CID national director, commissioner Chrispen Charumbira,  was arrested in September last year on allegations of accepting “protection money” from drug and gold dealers. He is currently on suspension while awaiting trial. Other senior police officers, assistant commissioner Obeylaw Moyo and superintendent Naboth Nyachega, were also arrested last year by Zacc on allegations of abuse of office and bribery. This was after they were implicated in a housing stands scandal which came to light after authorities busted several Harare City Council officials over malfeasance and sleaze. Last week, Zimbabwe was named among some of the most corrupt countries in the world in the Corruption Perception Index (CPI) for 2020. According to the latest barometer, which measures perceptions of corruption in public institutions, Zimbabwe is at position 157 out of the 180 examined nations. After the release of the corruption index, Makamure said Zacc still had a long way to go in bringing culprits to book. “Of course the score is not pleasing. Zimbabwe has to improve, the country definitely has to improve. “We are happy, though, with the steps that have been taken, and some of the achievements that we have realised. But we have a long way to go. “We fully agree with the recommendations from the CPI 2020 of strengthening oversight institutions. We need to prevent corruption. “We need our oversight institutions to be as strong as possible. They must be well capacitated to carry out their mandate. “Here, I’m talking about anti-corruption bodies, the Parliament of Zimbabwe and others. We fully agree also on the recommendation of open and transparent contracting in public procurement. That’s an area that we are prioritising as a commission in 2021,” Makamure said. Sponsored Links

    
      
        
          
